Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Logan Michale Swanson

records.addlTxt: 8:27 AM CO: RMW , REP: Melstrom, CLERK: Fox, Defendant Logan Michael Swanson in court.  Attorney Jeremiah James Harrelson in court for Logan Michael Swanson.  Prosecuting attorney Erica Ellenwood in court for the State of Wisconsin. Court reads charge and maximum penalty. DE pleads GUILTY to Count 1 . DE sworn. Crt reviews plea questionnaire and informs DE of rights. Crt finds DE freely, voluntarily and knowingly waives rights and makes plea. Recess at 8:32 am for Def to review agreement. Case recalled at 8:45 am.  Attorney's stipulate to the facts. Crt accepts plea, finds factual basis and finds DE guilty of Count 1. Def has reviewed and signed DJOC. Atty Harrelson states a PH has not been held. Court address Preliminary hearing and finds Def freely, voluntarily and knowingly waives preliminary hearing. Crt finds probable cause and binds Def over for trial. The State to file INFORMATION. Court withholds entry of judgment in favor of successful completion of 2 year Deferred Agreement. Court approves and signs agreement.
